    "summary": "Winston Churchill delivered his Iron Curtain speech — formally titled The Sinews of Peace — at Westminster College in Fulton, Missouri, on March 5, 1946, with President Truman on the platform. The speech gave a name and a vivid image to the division of Europe that had developed since the end of [[event:112|World War II]]: an iron curtain had descended across the Continent, stretching from Stettin in the Baltic to Trieste in the Adriatic, with Soviet-dominated states lying east of that line.\n\nChurchill's speech was widely seen as one of the opening declarations of the [[event:113|Cold War]], clearly articulating the Western perspective that Soviet power represented a threat to freedom and democratic values. Churchill called for a special relationship between Britain and the United States to counter Soviet expansion. The speech provoked immediate controversy: Stalin called Churchill a warmonger and compared him to Hitler; American progressives criticized it as anti-Soviet provocation.\n\nThe speech accurately described the political reality of Soviet dominance in Eastern Europe but also contributed to the hardening of Cold War divisions by framing the Soviet-American rivalry in stark ideological terms. The iron curtain metaphor proved extraordinarily durable, defining the mental map of European division for the next forty-five years until the curtain was lifted by the revolutions of 1989.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iron_Curtain",
